WEBVTT

00:00.000 --> 00:21.880
Cambridge Discovery readers, starter level, Gone by Margaret Johnson, published by Cambridge

00:21.880 --> 00:24.000
University Press.

00:24.000 --> 00:46.060
This recording is copyright.

00:46.060 --> 00:56.380
Chapter One, Birthday Boy I'm sorry I'm working on your birthday, Tom.

00:56.380 --> 01:04.660
Tom's mother is leaving the house. She isn't looking at Tom. She's thinking about work.

01:04.660 --> 01:10.580
Have a nice day, love. See you tonight, she says.

01:10.580 --> 01:19.280
Goodbye mum, Tom says. He feels sad. He doesn't want her to go.

01:19.280 --> 01:23.920
Tom's sister, Annie, comes down from her room.

01:23.920 --> 01:30.360
Happy birthday, little brother, she says. 12 today.

01:30.360 --> 01:35.200
Tom smiles. He likes being 12.

01:35.200 --> 01:41.160
Can I give you your birthday present this afternoon? Annie asks. I'm going shopping

01:41.160 --> 01:47.200
this morning with my friends. She goes to the door.

01:47.200 --> 01:53.800
I want to go shopping. Tom starts to say, but Annie doesn't hear.

01:53.800 --> 02:00.500
Enjoy your birthday, she says. Then she leaves too.

02:00.500 --> 02:08.980
Now Tom's father is the only person at home. Tom finds him at his desk. He's working on

02:08.980 --> 02:18.420
his computer. Tom's father works at home and he works all the time.

02:18.420 --> 02:24.180
Tom walks into his father's office and his father turns and looks at him.

02:24.340 --> 02:31.300
Hello, Tom, he says. What are you going to do with your birthday money?

02:31.300 --> 02:37.380
I don't know, Dad. Tom says. Can we go shopping?

02:37.380 --> 02:41.780
Tom's father is looking at his computer again.

02:41.780 --> 02:48.580
Not today, Tom, he says. I must finish this work. Where's Annie?

02:48.580 --> 02:56.660
She's shopping with her friends, Tom says. He knows his father isn't listening. He's reading

02:56.660 --> 03:05.860
an email on his computer. That's nice, he says. But he doesn't look at Tom. Have a good time.

03:06.820 --> 03:17.700
Okay, says Tom and he leaves the room. Tom phones his friend, Neil. Neil's mother answers.

03:17.700 --> 03:28.660
Can I speak to Neil? Tom asks. I'm sorry, Neil's mother says. He's playing football in Winston Park.

03:29.460 --> 03:38.580
Is that Tom? Yes, says Tom. Neil tells me it's your birthday today, Neil's mother says.

03:39.540 --> 03:48.900
Happy birthday. Thank you, says Tom. I must go, but have a good day, says Neil's mother.

03:49.940 --> 03:53.860
Thank you, Tom says again, and he puts the phone down.

03:53.860 --> 04:04.100
No one has any time for me today, he thinks. It's my birthday and no one has any time for me.

04:06.260 --> 04:08.740
Chapter 2. The Camera

04:11.780 --> 04:19.780
Tom leaves the house and walks to Winston Park. He doesn't like football, but he wants to be with

04:19.860 --> 04:28.420
people. It's a hot day. In Winston Park, there are lots of mothers and fathers with their children.

04:29.300 --> 04:34.100
Boys and girls are running and laughing. Everyone looks happy.

04:35.620 --> 04:39.940
Tom sees Neil and some more boys. They're playing football.

04:40.020 --> 04:50.820
Tom goes over. Neil sees him. He smiles. Hello, Tom. He calls. Happy birthday.

04:52.660 --> 04:57.220
Thank you, Tom calls, but Neil is running to get the ball.

04:58.820 --> 05:03.860
Tom watches the game for 10 minutes, but Neil doesn't speak to him again.

05:04.820 --> 05:08.020
Neil's good at football, and he's enjoying the game.

05:09.940 --> 05:17.780
Tom starts walking across Winston Park. He sits down on a seat and takes a drink from his bag.

05:19.300 --> 05:26.020
He puts his bag down. There is another bag under the seat. What's this?

05:26.660 --> 05:34.580
thinks Tom. The bag is black. Tom opens it. He's looking for a name.

05:35.940 --> 05:42.260
There is only one thing in the bag. A camera. Tom takes it out.

05:43.460 --> 05:49.060
Then he looks in the bag again, but there is nothing in it. No name.

05:49.620 --> 05:58.500
Tom looks at the camera. There are four buttons. Photo, delete, on, and off.

06:00.180 --> 06:06.340
Tom puts his finger on the on button and presses it. The camera makes a noise.

06:07.780 --> 06:12.580
The black bag is on the seat. Tom can see it in the camera.

06:13.220 --> 06:21.300
Tom puts his finger on the photo button. He presses it. The camera makes another noise.

06:21.300 --> 06:28.900
Tom looks at the photo of the bag. It's okay, but he doesn't want a photo of a bag,

06:28.900 --> 06:34.020
so he presses the delete button. The photo goes away.

06:34.020 --> 06:40.740
This camera is okay, Tom thinks. But it isn't my camera.

06:41.540 --> 06:47.140
I must take it to the police. I can buy a camera with my birthday money.

06:48.580 --> 06:54.820
Tom puts out his hand to take the camera bag from the seat, but the bag isn't there.

06:56.260 --> 07:01.780
He looks under the seat. No bag. He looks behind the seat.

07:02.580 --> 07:09.940
No bag. Tom doesn't understand. Where is the bag? He thinks.

07:11.700 --> 07:18.420
A squirrel runs in front of the seat. Tom wants a photo of it. The squirrel stops.

07:19.940 --> 07:26.180
It's looking for food, Tom thinks. He smiles and presses the photo button.

07:27.220 --> 07:30.020
But when he looks at the photo, it isn't good.

07:31.700 --> 07:37.620
Squirrels are too fast for photos, Tom thinks. He presses the delete button.

07:38.420 --> 07:45.540
The photo of the squirrel goes away. When Tom looks for the squirrel, he can't see it.

07:47.140 --> 07:53.060
Squirrels run fast, Tom thinks. But not that fast. Where is it?

07:54.580 --> 07:59.780
Tom looks at the camera. He doesn't understand. Something is wrong.

08:00.980 --> 08:06.260
He wants to try the camera again. There are some flowers next to his seat.

08:07.220 --> 08:10.980
Tom looks at the camera again. He can see the flowers.

08:12.020 --> 08:16.340
He presses the photo button and takes a photo of the flowers.

08:17.700 --> 08:21.780
Then he presses the delete button to make the photo go away.

08:23.380 --> 08:30.340
Tom takes the camera away from his face. He looks for the flowers. They aren't there.

08:30.500 --> 08:36.580
The flowers are gone, he thinks. Gone.

08:39.380 --> 08:42.180
Chapter 3. Where's the ball?

08:45.460 --> 08:51.860
Tom puts the camera down. He doesn't want it in his hands now. He feels afraid.

08:52.900 --> 08:57.220
He thinks about the camera bag, the squirrel and the flowers.

08:58.020 --> 09:07.220
When I take photos of things with this camera, they go away. He thinks, I don't know how, but they do.

09:08.420 --> 09:12.820
Across Winston Park, he can see the boys playing football.

09:13.780 --> 09:22.340
I must tell Neil about this, he thinks. He puts the camera in his bag and starts running across the park.

09:23.620 --> 09:26.180
But after a minute, he stops running.

09:27.220 --> 09:31.060
He thinks about the camera bag, the squirrel and the flowers.

09:32.340 --> 09:37.380
He's near the boys now. It's my birthday, he thinks.

09:38.340 --> 09:46.100
I want Neil to come to the shops with me. We can get a pizza. I can buy something with my birthday money.

09:48.820 --> 09:55.940
A boy in a blue t-shirt has the ball now. He's running fast. Then everyone shouts,

09:56.740 --> 10:04.980
go. Lots of the boys run to the boy in the blue t-shirt. They are all very happy.

10:06.340 --> 10:12.500
Tom quickly takes the camera from the bag and looks into it. He can see the ball.

10:14.100 --> 10:22.100
He presses the photo button and then the delete button. The boys want to start playing again.

10:23.060 --> 10:28.020
Hey, shouts the boy in the blue t-shirt. Where's the ball?

10:29.860 --> 10:35.140
No one can understand. They look on the grass and behind trees.

10:36.820 --> 10:39.540
Can you see the ball, Tom? Neil asks.

10:40.740 --> 10:48.820
No, sorry, Tom says. I don't know where the ball is. I don't think you can play now.

10:49.620 --> 10:55.540
Do you want to get a pizza with me? I can buy something to eat with my birthday money.

10:57.140 --> 11:02.180
But Neil doesn't hear Tom. He's listening to the boy in the blue t-shirt.

11:03.220 --> 11:07.540
It's okay, he says. I've got another ball in my bag.

11:08.660 --> 11:15.700
Good, says Neil. But where is our other ball? I don't know, says the boy.

11:16.660 --> 11:20.980
He gets the new ball from his bag. They start to play again.

11:22.580 --> 11:27.860
Tom thinks about taking a new photo. A photo of the new ball.

11:28.900 --> 11:34.900
But the boys run away across the grass and Tom turns and starts to walk home.

11:35.860 --> 11:39.620
Chapter four, the computer.

11:42.020 --> 11:46.020
When Tom gets home, his father is making a coffee.

11:47.060 --> 11:50.980
Tom, is that you? He calls.

11:51.620 --> 11:57.860
Yes, Tom answers. Do you want a coffee? His father asks.

11:58.340 --> 12:04.740
No, thank you, answers, Tom. I'm just getting something from my room.

12:06.340 --> 12:11.620
Tom quickly runs up to his father's office. It's the room with the computer.

12:12.740 --> 12:17.380
He takes the camera from his bag. He can see the computer in it.

12:18.260 --> 12:21.700
He quickly presses photo, then delete.

12:22.580 --> 12:28.740
He looks at the table. No computer. Good, he thinks.

12:30.500 --> 12:35.300
Tom's father comes into the room with his coffee. He smiles at Tom.

12:36.420 --> 12:44.020
Okay, he asks. Then he stops smiling. Where's my computer? He asks.

12:44.100 --> 12:50.260
I don't know, says Tom. I don't understand.

12:51.060 --> 12:56.180
Tom's father says. Where is it? He looks behind Tom.

12:57.140 --> 13:05.060
He looks under the table. He looks all over the room. Then he looks at Tom.

13:05.940 --> 13:13.140
Tom, he says. Where's my computer? I don't know, answers, Tom.

13:14.660 --> 13:21.300
Computers don't just go. Tom's father says. Yes, they do, thinks Tom.

13:22.980 --> 13:28.340
Then he looks at his father. Can we go to the shops, Dad? He asks.

13:29.300 --> 13:36.420
No, Tom, his father says. I must find my computer. I'm going to phone the police.

13:37.620 --> 13:42.340
After the police come, Tom says. Can we go to the shops then?

13:43.860 --> 13:47.540
But Tom's father can't stop thinking about his computer.

13:49.060 --> 13:57.860
Please, Tom, he says. He looks tired. I know it's your birthday, but all my work is on that computer.

13:58.580 --> 14:01.940
It's very important. I don't know what to do.

14:03.860 --> 14:05.300
Tom looks at his father.

14:06.340 --> 14:11.460
I'm sorry, Dad, he says. His father smiles a little.

14:12.820 --> 14:17.940
It's okay, son, he says. Go and enjoy your birthday.

14:19.540 --> 14:27.380
Tom leaves the room. I can't enjoy my birthday, he thinks. No one has any time for me.

14:28.980 --> 14:37.060
Tom goes to his room and sits on his bed. Then he thinks about his mother and he knows what he

14:37.060 --> 14:43.380
wants to do. Chapter 5 Trying to Help

14:46.500 --> 14:52.500
Tom leaves the house and walks to his mother's cafe, Kathy's coffee shop.

14:52.500 --> 14:59.700
The cafe sells food all day. Lots of people go there on Saturdays.

15:00.900 --> 15:08.980
Tom can see his mother in the cafe. She looks hot. There are people at all the tables and they're

15:08.980 --> 15:19.220
all waiting for their food. Mum's tired, Tom thinks. She works a lot. He goes into the cafe.

15:20.100 --> 15:27.460
His mother sees him. Hello, Tom, she says. Why are you here on your birthday?

15:28.660 --> 15:33.860
I'm here to help you, he says. His mother smiles.

15:35.060 --> 15:42.740
Oh, thank you, Tom, she says. People want plates and cups for their food and drinks,

15:42.820 --> 15:50.420
she says. They're all dirty. She takes Tom to the dirty plates and cups in the kitchen.

15:51.700 --> 16:01.620
Can you wash them for me? She asks. Tom smiles. Of course, he says. Tom's mother smiles again.

16:03.220 --> 16:07.860
You're a good boy, she says. Then she leaves the kitchen.

16:08.820 --> 16:11.780
Tom quickly takes the camera from his bag.

16:13.460 --> 16:20.180
I can have an afternoon with mum, he thinks. We can go to a restaurant or watch a film.

16:21.780 --> 16:28.820
He can see the dirty cups and plates in the camera. He presses photo, then delete.

16:29.780 --> 16:32.900
Then he takes the camera away and looks.

16:33.140 --> 16:39.060
Gone, he thinks. They're gone. And he smiles.

16:40.740 --> 16:44.980
His mother comes back into the kitchen. She looks all over the room.

16:46.100 --> 16:53.060
Tom, she says. Where are the cups and plates? Tom thinks for a few seconds.

16:54.180 --> 16:59.780
It's the camera, he tells her. When I take a photo, things go away.

17:00.500 --> 17:04.500
His mother looks at him. She looks very tired now.

17:05.700 --> 17:15.220
What? She asks. I don't understand. The camera, Tom starts. But his mother speaks.

17:16.180 --> 17:23.220
Tom, she says. There aren't any plates or cups and there are lots of people in the cafe.

17:24.020 --> 17:27.860
What am I going to do? Close the cafe mum.

17:28.020 --> 17:34.740
Close the cafe mum. Tom says. We can go out. His mother is angry now.

17:35.940 --> 17:41.140
I can't close the cafe, Tom. She says. This is my job.

17:42.180 --> 17:45.860
Now please, tell me where the cups and plates are.

17:46.980 --> 17:51.780
I don't know mum. Tom starts saying. It's the camera.

17:51.940 --> 17:56.340
The door opens. Tom's sister comes in.

17:57.380 --> 17:59.940
Hello, she says. What's wrong?

18:01.060 --> 18:04.820
Tom's mother starts telling Annie about the plates and cups.

18:05.620 --> 18:09.220
But Annie isn't listening. She sees Tom's camera.

18:10.420 --> 18:14.500
What's this? She says. And takes it from her brother.

18:15.380 --> 18:20.980
Is it new? Give it to me. Tom says. Annie doesn't listen.

18:22.100 --> 18:28.260
She puts the camera to her eye. She looks at Tom. Smile, she says.

18:29.940 --> 18:34.180
No, Tom shouts. Annie presses the photo button.

18:35.220 --> 18:40.420
Give the camera to me, Annie. Tom shouts. Annie looks at the photo.

18:41.460 --> 18:48.420
This isn't a good photo of you, Tom. Annie says. No, don't press any buttons.

18:48.420 --> 18:58.260
Shouts, Tom. But it's too late. Annie presses. Delete.

